	measuring their performance for each design. The most common
	problem is that people learn over time, and so they
	frequently perform better on the 2nd design than the first,
	regardless of the relative quality of the designs. Thus, it's
	important to counterbalance such a study, having half the
	subjects start with one design and half start with the other,
	in order to avoid having the order effects give an advantage
	to one design.

	related: {between-subjects design} {confound} {Hawthorne effect} {internal validity}

	categories: <Empirical Methods> <Empirical Methods>

between-subjects design

	[1092]
	a study designed to make a comparison of 2 or more designs
	and that compares them by having one set of users try one
