aesthetic integrity

	[314]
	a principle that advocates that a design should be visually
	appealing and should follow common principles of visual
	design: consistency, a clear identity, a clear visual
	hierarchy, good alignment, contrast, and proportions, etc.

	What constitutes an aesthetically successful design may vary
	with the application and the audience. A bright and active
	design may work well for attracting people to store-front
	displays, but a softer, more soothing design will be far more
	successful for applications that people need to use all day
	long.

	As with all design principles, aesthetics needs to be
	carefully balanced with other requirements, such as providing
	adequate information when it is most useful and avoiding
	confusing the user.

	Note that aesthetic integrity is not merely "attractiveness".
	It implies a visual design that is coherent and
	well-structured.

